WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.020
E aí, você tem que saber analisar o perfil.

2
00:00:02.459 --> 00:00:04.259
Existem alguns tipos de pessoa, né?

3
00:00:04.259 --> 00:00:07.259
A gente chama dos takers, os givers e os matchers, né?

4
00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:10.439
Os takers são aquelas pessoas que vão fazer network.

5
00:00:10.580 --> 00:00:11.939
Beleza, e o que você agrega para mim?

6
00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:13.220
Esse é o taker, né?

7
00:00:13.660 --> 00:00:17.160
E o giver é aquela pessoa que está querendo dar e tudo mais.

8
00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:18.559
E tem os matchers, né?

9
00:00:18.620 --> 00:00:20.679
Os matchers são aquela pessoa que troca.

10
00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:23.760
Tipo assim, beleza, eu te ajudo, mas o que você vai me ajudar em troca, né?

11
00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:24.879
Qual que é a moeda aqui?

12
00:00:45.299 --> 00:00:45.359
Então, esses são alguns perfis. PERFÍSES na carreira, no empreendedorismo, etc. Muitas das pessoas acham que é o matcher, né?

13
00:00:47.719 --> 00:00:48.020
Mas não, a cadeia começa assim, a base é de givers, né?

14
00:00:49.899 --> 00:00:50.259
Logo acima dos givers vem os takers,

15
00:00:51.899 --> 00:00:52.359
porque aí é aquele ditado,

16
00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:54.679
quando tem o encontro do malandro com o otário, né?

17
00:00:56.640 --> 00:00:56.759
O encontro perfeito, porque aí o giver quer dar,

18
00:00:59.179 --> 00:00:59.439
o taker quer tomar, então ele se aproveita do giver.

19
00:01:01.460 --> 00:01:01.859
Então o taker começa a se aproveitar do giver.

20
00:01:03.420 --> 00:01:03.880
E aí acima deles vem o matcher,

21
00:01:06.019 --> 00:01:06.060
que aí ele consegue dosar e falar assim,

22
00:01:08.799 --> 00:01:08.879
não, o taker, beleza, a gente troca alguma coisa,

23
00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:10.180
mas você também tem que me ajudar.

24
00:01:11.939 --> 00:01:12.340
Então ele consegue fazer a negociação.

25
00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:15.579
Mas acima de todos os três, tem uma nova cadeia de givers,

26
00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:24.019
que são os givers que aprenderam a não deixar os takers sobreporem eles e darem tudo a troco de nada.

27
00:01:24.379 --> 00:01:27.400
Então os givers que conseguiram entender limites,

28
00:01:27.799 --> 00:01:31.200
eles são as pessoas que mais ascendem e vão para o topo da cadeia.

29
00:01:31.579 --> 00:01:34.400
Então, a posição mais nobre ali é o giver,

30
00:01:34.799 --> 00:01:37.079
desde que, dentro da sua organização,

31
00:01:37.439 --> 00:01:40.819
você consiga tirar essa cultura do taker.

32
00:01:40.959 --> 00:01:43.620
Na hora que você tira isso aqui da equação,

33
00:01:43.620 --> 00:01:57.400
os givers prosperam e acabam ascendendo ao topo da cadeia. Então você tem que proteger os fornecedores no seu meio.

34
00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:01.280
E eu aprendi uma ótima lição sobre isso, do melhor networker da Fortune.

35
00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:04.420
É o cara, não o gato.

36
00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:07.739
Seu nome é Adam Rifkin.

37
00:02:07.760 --> 00:02:09.879
He's a very successful serial entrepreneur

38
00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:12.520
who spends a huge amount of his time helping other people.

39
00:02:12.539 --> 00:02:14.879
And his secret weapon is the five-minute favor.

40
00:02:15.539 --> 00:02:19.259
Adam said, look, you don't have to be Mother Teresa or Gandhi to be a giver.

41
00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:23.159
You just have to find small ways to add large value to other people's lives.

42
00:02:23.180 --> 00:02:25.500
And that could be as simple as making an introduction

43
00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:28.379
between two people who could benefit from knowing each other.

44
00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:31.500
It could be sharing your knowledge or giving a little bit of feedback.

45
00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:33.900
Or it might be even something as basic as saying,

46
00:02:33.919 --> 00:02:37.020
you know, I'm going to try to figure out if I can recognize

47
00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:39.280
somebody whose work has gone unnoticed.

48
00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:42.500
And those five-minute favors are really critical

49
00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:45.560
to helping givers set boundaries and protect themselves.

50
00:02:46.719 --> 00:02:46.979
And the second thing that matters,

51
00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:48.939
if you want to build a culture where givers succeed,

52
00:02:51.300 --> 00:02:51.659
is you actually need a culture where help-seeking is the norm,

53
00:02:52.939 --> 00:02:53.800
where people ask a lot.

54
00:02:56.259 --> 00:03:00.219
This may hit a little too close to home for some of you.

55
00:03:01.979 --> 00:03:05.120
What you see with successful givers is they recognize that it's okay to be a receiver too.

56
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:08.319
And if you run an organization, we can actually make this easier.

57
00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:10.180
We can make it easier for people to ask for help.

58
00:03:10.659 --> 00:03:12.300
A couple of colleagues and I studied hospitals,

59
00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:15.699
and we found that on certain floors, nurses did a lot of help-seeking,

60
00:03:15.919 --> 00:03:17.800
and on other floors, they did very little of it.

61
00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:20.900
And the factor that stood out on the floors where help-seeking was common,

62
00:03:21.099 --> 00:03:21.879
where it was the norm,

63
00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:24.639
was there was just one nurse whose sole job it was

64
00:03:24.639 --> 00:03:27.199
to help other nurses on the unit. And when thateking was common, where it was the norm, was there was just one nurse whose sole job it was to help other nurses on the unit.

65
00:03:27.199 --> 00:03:28.979
And when that role was available, nurses said,

66
00:03:28.979 --> 00:03:31.139
oh, it's not embarrassing, it's not vulnerable

67
00:03:31.139 --> 00:03:33.639
to ask for help, it's actually encouraged.

68
00:03:34.639 --> 00:03:37.060
Now, help-seeking isn't important just for protecting

69
00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:38.979
the success and the well-being of givers.

70
00:03:38.979 --> 00:03:40.599
It's also critical to getting more people

71
00:03:40.599 --> 00:03:43.060
to act like givers, because the data say

72
00:03:43.060 --> 00:03:47.500
that somewhere between 75 and 90% of all giving in organizations starts with a request.

73
00:03:48.419 --> 00:03:49.800
But a lot of people don't ask.

74
00:03:49.819 --> 00:03:51.520
They don't want to look incompetent,

75
00:03:51.539 --> 00:03:54.419
they don't know where to turn, they don't want to burden others.

76
00:03:54.439 --> 00:03:56.199
And yet, if nobody ever asked for help,

77
00:03:56.219 --> 00:03:58.719
you have a lot of frustrated givers in your organization

78
00:03:58.740 --> 00:04:00.699
who would love to step up and contribute

79
00:04:00.719 --> 00:04:02.979
if they only knew who could benefit and how.

80
00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:05.240
But I think the most important thing,

81
00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:07.639
if you want to build a culture of successful givers,

82
00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:10.479
is to be thoughtful about who you let onto your team.

83
00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:13.120
I figured, you want a culture of productive generosity,

84
00:04:13.139 --> 00:04:15.379
you should hire a bunch of givers.

85
00:04:15.419 --> 00:04:19.420
But I was surprised to discover, actually, that that was not right.

86
00:04:19.459 --> 00:04:21.879
That the negative impact of a taker on a culture

87
00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:25.180
is usually double to triple the positive impact of a giver.

88
00:04:25.199 --> 00:04:26.500
Think about it this way.

89
00:04:26.519 --> 00:04:27.899
One bad apple can spoil a barrel,

90
00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:30.759
but one good egg just does not make a dozen.

91
00:04:31.579 --> 00:04:33.060
I don't know what that means.

92
00:04:34.199 --> 00:04:35.560
But I hope you do.

93
00:04:35.579 --> 00:04:38.819
No, let even one taker into a team,

94
00:04:38.839 --> 00:04:42.019
and you will see that the givers will stop helping.

95
00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:44.980
They'll say, I'm surrounded by a bunch of snakes and sharks,

96
00:04:49.360 --> 00:04:53.060
why should I contribute? Whereas if you let one giver into a team, you don't get an explosion of generosity. More often people are like, great, that person can do all our work.

97
00:04:54.180 --> 00:04:59.680
So effective hiring and team building is not about bringing in the givers. It's about weeding

98
00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:04.879
out the takers. And if you can do that well, you'll be left with givers and matchers. The

99
00:05:04.879 --> 00:05:05.319
givers will be generous because they don't have to worry about the consequencesers. And if you can do that well, you'll be left with givers and matchers.

100
00:05:05.339 --> 00:05:09.139
The givers will be generous because they don't have to worry about the consequences.

101
00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:12.100
And the beauty of the matchers is that they follow the norm.

102
00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:15.420
So how do you catch a taker before it's too late?

103
00:05:15.439 --> 00:05:18.220
We're actually pretty bad at figuring out who's a taker,

104
00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:20.060
especially on first impressions.

105
00:05:20.079 --> 00:05:22.519
And there's a personality trait that throws us off.

106
00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:23.860
It's called agreeableness,

107
00:05:23.879 --> 00:05:26.459
one of the major dimensions of personality across cultures.

108
00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:29.699
Agreeable people are warm and friendly, they're nice, they're polite.

109
00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:31.360
You find a lot of them in Canada.

110
00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:36.560
Where there was actually a national contest

111
00:05:36.579 --> 00:05:41.060
to come up with a new Canadian slogan and fill in the blank as Canadian as ...

112
00:05:41.079 --> 00:05:43.180
And I thought the winning entry was going to be

113
00:05:43.199 --> 00:05:46.639
as Canadian as maple syrup or ice hockey. But no, Canadians voted for their new national slogan to be,

114
00:05:46.660 --> 00:05:47.660
I kid you not,

115
00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:50.240
as Canadian as possible under the circumstances.

116
00:05:54.500 --> 00:05:56.339
Now, for those of you who are highly agreeable,

117
00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:58.060
or maybe slightly Canadian,

118
00:05:58.079 --> 00:05:59.540
you get this right away.

119
00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:01.339
How could I ever say I'm any one thing

120
00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:04.740
when I'm constantly adapting to try to please other people?

121
00:06:04.759 --> 00:06:06.019
Disagreeable people do less of it. They're more critical, skeptical, challenging, I get this right away. How could I ever say I'm any one thing when I'm constantly adapting to try to please other people?

122
00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:07.819
Disagreeable people do less of it.

123
00:06:07.839 --> 00:06:10.720
They're more critical, skeptical, challenging,

124
00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:13.759
and far more likely than their peers to go to law school.

125
00:06:14.939 --> 00:06:17.519
That's not a joke, that's actually an empirical fact.

126
00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:20.500
So I always assumed that agreeable people were givers

127
00:06:20.519 --> 00:06:23.079
and disagreeable people were takers.

128
00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:24.579
But then I gathered the data,

129
00:06:24.600 --> 00:06:27.579
and I was stunned to find no correlation between those traits.

130
00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:30.180
Because it turns out that agreeableness-disagreeableness

131
00:06:30.199 --> 00:06:31.360
is your outer veneer.

132
00:06:31.379 --> 00:06:33.220
How pleasant is it to interact with you?

133
00:06:33.240 --> 00:06:36.000
Whereas giving and taking are more of your inner motives.

134
00:06:36.019 --> 00:06:38.860
What are your values? What are your intentions toward others?

135
00:06:38.879 --> 00:06:40.939
If you really want to judge people accurately,

136
00:06:40.959 --> 00:06:44.699
you have to get to the moment that every consultant in the room is waiting for

137
00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:50.240
and draw a two by two.

138
00:06:54.319 --> 00:06:56.160
The agreeable givers are easy to spot. They say yes to everything.

139
00:06:59.519 --> 00:07:02.560
The disagreeable takers are also recognized quickly, although you might call them by a slightly different name.

140
00:07:06.240 --> 00:07:08.420
We forget about the other two combinations.

141
00:07:08.439 --> 00:07:11.560
There are disagreeable givers in our organizations.

142
00:07:11.579 --> 00:07:14.220
They're people who are gruff and tough on the surface,

143
00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:17.220
but underneath have others' best interests at heart.

144
00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:18.620
Or as an engineer put it,

145
00:07:18.639 --> 00:07:19.980
oh, disagreeable givers,

146
00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.240
like somebody with a bad user interface,

147
00:07:22.259 --> 00:07:24.000
but a great operating system.

148
00:07:25.339 --> 00:07:26.600
If that helps you.

149
00:07:28.360 --> 00:07:31.680
Disagreeable givers are the most undervalued people in our organizations

150
00:07:31.699 --> 00:07:34.139
because they're the ones who give the critical feedback

151
00:07:34.160 --> 00:07:36.819
that no one wants to hear, but everyone needs to hear.

152
00:07:36.839 --> 00:07:39.300
We need to do a much better job valuing these people

153
00:07:39.319 --> 00:07:41.540
as opposed to writing them off early and saying,

154
00:07:41.560 --> 00:07:44.240
eh, kind of prickly, must be a selfish taker.

155
00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:47.480
The other combination we forget about is the deadly one,

156
00:07:47.699 --> 00:07:50.399
the agreeable taker, also known as the faker.

157
00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:53.420
This is the person who's nice to your face

158
00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:55.139
and then will stab you right in the back.

159
00:07:57.560 --> 00:08:00.779
And my favorite way to catch these people in the interview process

160
00:08:00.779 --> 00:08:02.120
is to ask the question,

161
00:08:02.279 --> 00:08:03.879
can you give me the names of four people

162
00:08:03.879 --> 00:08:09.079
whose careers you have fundamentally improved? And the takers will give you four names,

163
00:08:09.240 --> 00:08:14.300
and they will all be more influential than them, because takers are great at kissing up and then

164
00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:18.779
kicking down. Givers are more likely to name people who are below them in a hierarchy,

165
00:08:19.139 --> 00:08:23.839
who don't have as much power, who can do them no good. And let's face it, you all know you can

166
00:08:23.839 --> 00:08:28.180
learn a lot about character by watching how someone treats their restaurant server or their Uber driver.

167
00:08:29.819 --> 00:08:33.759
So if we do all this well, if we can weed takers out of organizations, if we can make it safe

168
00:08:33.759 --> 00:08:39.019
to ask for help, if we can protect givers from burnout and make it okay for them to be ambitious

169
00:08:39.019 --> 00:08:43.639
in pursuing their own goals, as well as trying to help other people, we can actually change the way

170
00:08:43.639 --> 00:08:45.419
that people define success.

171
00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:48.659
Instead of saying it's all about winning a competition,

172
00:08:48.679 --> 00:08:52.039
people will realize success is really more about contribution.

173
00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:55.279
I believe that the most meaningful way to succeed

174
00:08:55.299 --> 00:08:57.120
is to help other people succeed.

175
00:08:57.139 --> 00:08:58.679
And if we can spread that belief,

176
00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:01.419
we can actually turn paranoia upside down.

177
00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:03.779
There's a name for that. It's called pronoia.

178
00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:05.039
Pronoia.

179
00:09:06.639 --> 00:09:06.659
Pronoia is the delusional belief

180
00:09:09.179 --> 00:09:12.840
that other people are plotting your well-being.

181
00:09:15.279 --> 00:09:15.299
That they're going around behind your back

182
00:09:18.179 --> 00:09:19.399
and saying exceptionally glowing things about you.

183
00:09:21.940 --> 00:09:21.960
And the great thing about a culture of givers is

184
00:09:24.159 --> 00:09:25.019
that's not a delusão, é realidade.

185
00:09:47.879 --> 00:09:49.960
Olha, eu quero viver em um mundo onde donadores conseguem, como ele chama que tá todo mundo achando que tem alguém falando

186
00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:52.019
nas suas costas, mas dessa vez a gente tá achando que tá falando bem

187
00:09:52.019 --> 00:09:53.840
a gente vai ter muito mais incentivos

188
00:09:53.840 --> 00:09:55.860
muito mais vontade de fazer as coisas irem

189
00:09:55.860 --> 00:09:57.320
pro próximo nível, as coisas crescerem

190
00:09:57.320 --> 00:09:58.720
tranquilidade, né?
